              <a href="https://book.douban.com/annotation/44980780/" class="">第600页</a></h3>
          </div>
          <div class="clst">
            <p class="user"><a href="https://www.douban.com/people/148495268/" class=" " title="Minervaの鸮">Minervaの鸮</a>
              
            </p>
            <div class="reading-note" data-cid="44980780">
              <div class="short">
                
                  <div class="ll">
                    <a href="https://book.douban.com/annotation/44980780/"><img src="https://img3.doubanio.com/view/page_note/small/public/p44980780-1.jpg"></a>
                  </div>
                  <span class=""></span>
                <p class="pl">
                  <span class="">2017-06-17 16:43</span>
                  
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="all hidden" style="display:none" >
                <div class="image-container image-float-center"><div class="image-wrapper"><img src="https://img3.doubanio.com/view/page_note/large/public/p44980780-1.jpg"></div><div class="image-caption-wrapper"><div class="image-caption">怪不得把单身者称为“狗”，单身狗一词近乎同义反复，在古希腊，狗就意味着与共同体相剥离的，这也是后来犬儒之所是，对共同体的漠不关心。苏格拉底喜欢凭狗起誓，这意味着什么呢？狗作为amor mundi反面的象征，与政治/哲学传统中行与思的分离又有着什么样的联系呢？</div></div></div>
                  <div class="col-rec-con clearfix">
                    







<div class="rec-sec">

    <span class="rec">

<a href="https://www.douban.com/accounts/register?reason=collect" class="j a_show_login lnk-sharing lnk-douban-sharing">推荐</a>
</span>
</div>

                  </div>
